ong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Euphemia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of a Late Greek name derived from <i>eu</i> ‘well, good’ + <i>phēnai</i> ‘to speak’. This was the name of various early saints, notably a virgin martyr said to have been burned at the stake at Chalcedon in  307 . It had a limited popularity in some regions in the 16th and 17th centuries and returned to favour in the Victorian period, especially in the pet form   Effie .  It is little used at present."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Euphemia of Byzantium was born in 1070, her father, Aepa Khan of the Kumans, was 56 and her mother, Wife of Aepa, was 36. She married Volodymir II Monomakh Great Prince of Kiev in 1099, in Kyiv Ukraine Temple, Kyiv, Ukraine. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died on 7 May 1107, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1070–7 May 1107":"1070–7. mai 1107","1070–1107":"1070–1107","1053–1125":"1053–1125","1093–1157":"1093–1157","1095–1139":"1095–1139","1098–1118":"1098–1118","1099–1141":"1099–1141","1102–1141":"1102–1141","1015–Male":"1015–Surnud","1035–Female":"1035–Surnud","1099":"1099","1087":"1099","1098":"1098","1141":"1141","1053":"1053","7 May 1107":"7. mai 1107","1095":"1095","1093":"1093","1070":"1070","1118":"11